<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ephedra</i> <i>viridis</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Artemisia</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Chrysothamnus</i> <i>viscidiflorus</i>, <i>Ericameria</i> <i>nauseosa</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>heermannii</i>, <i>Gutierrezia</i> <i>microcephala</i>, <i>Opuntia</i> <i>polyacantha</i> var. <i>erinacea</i>, <i>Purshia</i> <i>glandulosa</i> and <i>Purshia</i> <i>stansburiana</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Juniperus</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Juniperus</i> <i>osteosperma</i> or <i>Pinus</i> <i>monophylla</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs 1-3 m; canopy is continuous to open. Herbaceous layer is sparse to open. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Ephedra viridis</i> > 30% relative cover (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Ridges, hills, mountains, channel beds. Soils are shallow derived from alluvium, granitic substrate, bedrock, colluvium.  </div>
</div>

        
