<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ephedra viridis </i>is an erect, evergreen shrub with wind-pollinated cones and small mammal-dispersed seeds. Seeds germinate after a period of cold stratification, and plants commonly sprout from roots and the woody crown. Shrub clumps may represent multiple clones originating from cached seed. Plants have several taproots and are deeply rooted (Anderson 2001e). <br/>
<br/>
This alliance is part of the Great Basin sagebrush scrub complex; the species and alliance are localized in high mountains of the northern and eastern Mojave Desert of California and are more widespread in the Great Basin. Compared to the <i>Artemisia tridentata </i>alliance in the same regions, <i>Ephedra viridis </i>alliance occurs on shallower, rocky soils that are well-drained and often granitic in origin, and not on deep residual or alluvial soils. It is intolerant of wet, poorly drained sites. Because of typically steep slopes, rock falls and avalanches may occasionally impact stands (Anderson 2001e, Thomas et al. 2004). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
