    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa, Ad, Af, Ah, Aj, Al, An). Stands are typically small, associated with rocky uplands at mid to high elevations in the section. Stands occur above 1300 m in the Funeral, Kingston, and Providence mountains (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341De-f, Dh, Dj, Dl). Stands are widespread on coarse, rocky volcanic substrates intermixed with <i>Pinus monophylla</i> alliance stands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er). Stands are common adjacent to <i>Pinus monophylla</i> and <i>Artemisia tridentata</i> stands on granitics along the eastern escarpment.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-f). Small stands exist interspersed with <i>Pinus monophylla</i> woodlands on cool, exposed sites and with <i>Artemisia tridentata</i> shrublands on less steep sites above 1200 m in the Cottonwood Mountains (Peterson 1984a, 1984b), and the Argus, Coso, Grapevine, and Inyo mountains (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Although fire is a natural but uncommon component of this alliance, large frequent fires are detrimental. Heavy grazing reduces intact shrubs, grasses, and herbaceous cover, and it allows non-native plant invasion. <i>Ephedra viridis </i>does not survive in areas with high herbaceous cover or with high salinities. The plant is a highly important browse plant and seeds are an important food source for small mammals. Projects to restore rangeland communities use cuttings, seed, and transplants of <i>E. viridis </i>(Anderson 2001e). </div>
</div>

    

    

